Link the final binaries with the C compiler driver, not raw ld.

aprx's Makefile.in sets LD=@CC@ and links the programs with $(LD), so upstream
the final link normally runs through the compiler driver. OpenWrt's build
overrides LD on the make command line (LD="..-ld.bfd"), which wins over the
Makefile assignment, so the link rule invokes ld.bfd directly:

  ..-ld.bfd ... -o aprx aprx.o ... -pthread
  ..-ld.bfd: unrecognized option '-pthread'

-pthread (and the -fuse-ld=bfd in LDFLAGS) are compiler-driver options, not
linker options; a threaded C program must be linked via $(CC) so the driver
adds the C runtime/crt objects and translates -pthread. Use $(CC) for the two
final-link rules. OpenWrt sets CC to the cross gcc, which honours -pthread and
-fuse-ld=bfd, so this links cleanly and is the portable, conventional form.

--- a/Makefile.in
+++ b/Makefile.in
@@ -99,10 +99,10 @@
 
 
 $(PROGAPRX):	$(OBJSAPRX) VERSION Makefile
-		$(LD) $(LDFLAGS) -o $@ $(OBJSAPRX) $(LIBS)
+		$(CC) $(LDFLAGS) -o $@ $(OBJSAPRX) $(LIBS)
 
 $(PROGSTAT):	$(OBJSSTAT) VERSION Makefile
-		$(LD) $(LDFLAGS) -o $@ $(OBJSSTAT) $(LIBS)
+		$(CC) $(LDFLAGS) -o $@ $(OBJSSTAT) $(LIBS)
 
 .PHONY:		man
 man:		$(MAN)
